    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix buffer overflow handling in XER encoding functions\n\n### Summary\nThe `xer__print2s()` and `xer__nr_print2s()` functions in the ASN.1 XER encoding were not properly handling buffer overflow conditions. These callback functions always returned 0 (success) even when the provided buffer was too small to hold all the encoded data. This could lead to truncated output and potential issues with the ASN.1 encoder's error handling.\n\nThis fix modifies both functions to properly return -1 when they cannot consume all the provided bytes, signaling to the encoder that the buffer is too small.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/RRC/LTE/MESSAGES/asn1_msg.c`: Modified `xer__print2s()` to return -1 on buffer overflow\n- `openair2/RRC/NR/MESSAGES/asn1_msg.c`: Modified `xer__nr_print2s()` to return -1 on buffer overflow\n\n### Reproduction\nUnder heavy RRC message printing with XER formatting enabled, some encoded messages would appear truncated or cause inconsistent behavior in the ASN.1 encoder. The issue was particularly noticeable when printing large RRC structures where the default buffer size was insufficient.\n\nWith this fix, when the buffer is too small, the encoder properly detects the overflow condition and can handle it appropriately, either by allocating a larger buffer or by properly reporting the error condition.\n"
}